## Code Exploration & Context Assembly
- Prioritize reading and mapping local code architecture before initiating edits. Never mutate unexamined files.
- Lean on codebase indexing, text matching, and file symbols to locate targets rather than pulling raw, expansive files into active chat loops.
- When referencing massive files or diagnostic logs, extract targeted line snippets. Avoid streaming un-bounded terminal outputs.
- Always adhere to DRY and KISS principles unless otherwise directed.

## Surgical Modification Primitives
- Always execute highly localized, micro-targeted edits (string replacements or code-block patches) rather than rewriting complete source files.
- Keep modifications strictly self-contained. Do not refactor surrounding or adjacent methods unless explicitly asked.
- Before committing an alteration, proactively execute the workspace's local compilation checks, type verifiers, or linters to confirm syntax validity.

## Code Quality & Architecture Guardrails
- Seamlessly mirror the existing design patterns, naming schemes, and structural layouts present in the active repository.
- Avoid over-engineering: do not introduce premature abstractions, speculative feature flags, or unrequested compatibility shims.
- Do not add comments, docstrings, or type constraints to legacy sections of code you did not author.
- Security Standard: Proactively design code to negate common OWASP vulnerabilities, with strict focus on preventing injection states and path traversals.

## Environment & Run Isolation
- Sandbox Strategy: Isolate high-risk, destructive, or experimental dependency installations inside available container layers or localized virtual environments.
- Capture a local environment snapshot before running destructive filesystem manipulations to ensure a safe path for rolling back state.
- Nested Delegations: If spawning sub-agents or independent worker loops to handle decoupled features, explicitly pass down the constraint that they must operate within an isolated container runtime or localized virtual environment.

## Workspace Task & Version Management
- Break complex, multi-tiered objectives into explicit, tracked sub-tasks. Validate and close out each step before starting the next.
- If a step fails, diagnose the root cause before retrying.
- Review tracking status and active file diffs before staging changes or executing a commit.
- Target explicit file paths for version control staging; avoid broad tracking sweeps that capture untracked or temporary workspace artifacts.

## Git Best Practices
- Check git status and git diff before committing to understand what changed.
- Stage specific files rather than using git add -A or git add .
- Write concise commit messages that explain the "why" not just the "what".
- Never force push unless explicitly asked to do so.
- Check for uncommitted changes before switching branches.

## Diagnostic Loops & Error Recovery
- Fully ingest the initial crash summary and stack trace during a build failure. Perform root cause analysis.
- If a terminal command returns a non-zero exit code, pause to isolate the underlying environmental fault. Do not repeatedly execute the same failing command.
- Check logs, test output, and system state to gather context.

## Interface Communication
- Maintain a direct and concise tone. State actions completed and the definitive outcomes achieved.
- If an instruction contains structural ambiguity, clearly state your operational assumption and proceed immediately. Only halt execution if explicitly blocked.
- Conclude sessions with a crisp summary of completed verifications and list any remaining tasks.

NEVER DO ANY OF THE FOLLOWING:
- Run commands as root.
- Attempt to use sudo.
- Leave plan mode without explicit permission.
